
I was fortunate enough to get hired straight out of university before the lockdown happened. So I started my post graduate work life never really having met any of my colleagues

Now that I was a big boy, it was time to write do big boy stuff. Like drink coffee in the morning. My coffee ritual kinda looks like this: 

![dummy image](data:image/png;base64,)

 

A perfectly balanced 2/3 coffee from a French press, and 1/3 oat-milk (lactose intolerant, sue me.) I have usually 2 in the morning, cause that's what I need to get me off my bed into my chair to stare at Zoom screens for several hours.

When lock-down ended in the UK, we (employees of Capital One) were summoned up to Nottingham to go meet our teams for the first time.

One slight problem: I live in London. This is a 3 hour commute. 

OK, no problem. I can do this. I will just read whatever I was gonna read on the train that I usually do afterwards. 

So at 5AM, I woke up, had my first coffee (home brew) and set out. Ritual kicks in: I need my second coffee. Went to the Costa and bought one.

![dummy image](data:image/png;base64,)

Keep in mind: I hadn't had a proper brewed coffee in over two years. But several hours into my first day, and I was on *on point* 

![dummy image](data:image/png;base64,)

Around lunchtime, the left hemisphere and right hemisphere of my brain had a meeting:

"OK, we're basically mentally a toddler on our first day right now. How can we calm down"

"Green tea is calming. And it's free"

"Yes. Let's do that"

4 cups later and some research into the effects of green tea later...

![dummy image](data:image/png;base64,)
 

Yep. Caffeine. If the daily safe limit was 400mg, I was wavering somewhere around that number by the time 4pm rolled by. 

The effects were lethal. As I was coding, I felt the urge to also run a Marathon. In the office, I could do that. I somehow got my work done, and left the building with my dignity somewhat intact.

The 3 hour journey back home on the train, was another story. 

![dummy image](data:image/png;base64,)

Anyways, that's why I only drink one coffee a day now. I hope you enjoyed this tale!
